727016f-c.title: Queens: Jamaica Avenue - 127th Street
727016f-c.text:
Jamaica Avenue, north side, between 127th and 130th Streets,
showing the Dow Sitmars House, built before the Revolution.
Dow Ditmars, son of John Ditmars, died about 1755. The house
was occupied by Pat Cary in 1860; by Mrs O'Connor in 1881; by
Domintcus Vandeveer in 1902; Adikes was the owner in 1923. The
house was demolished in late 1928.
1922
Views 1-2-3-4
Eugene L. Armbruster

727017f-a.title: Queens: Jamaica Avenue - 127th Street
727017f-a.text:
Jamaica Avenue, north side, between 127th and 130th Streets,
showing the Dow Ditmars House, a pre-Revolutionary structure. Dow
Ditmars married in 1687 and removed to Jamaica from Flatbush, where
he died about 1755. Later owners of the house were: Pat Cary, 1860;
Mrs. L. G. Blinck, 1872; Mra. O'Connor, 1891; Dominicus Vanderveer,
1902.
Views 1,2: 1923
Views 3,4: 1925
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

727018f-d.title: Queens: Jamaica Avenue - 127th Street
727018f-d.text:
Jamaica Avenue, north side, between 127th and 130th
Streets, showing the Dow Ditmars house. Some occupants
of this property were P. Cary 1860 and Mrs. L.G. Blinck
in 1872. Cther owners were Dominicus Vanderveer in 1881,
and Mrs. O'Conner in 1891. It was aold in 1891 and one
Adikes was the owner in 1922. The house was demolished
in October 1928. No. 3 looks east and shows the Long
Tsland Railroad embankment in the background. In View
No. 4 the B.M.T. Elevated structure is seen towering over
Jamaica Avenue.
View 1: 1922
Views 2,3,4: 1925
Eugene L. Armbruster Colleotion
